thumberland,England":"Widdrington, Northumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lady","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>lavedi</i>, <i>levedi</i>, <i>ladi</i> ‘lady, female head of a household, woman, wife’ (Old English <i>hlǣfdige</i>). As a man's name it may have been used in mockery, or be short for occupational names such as <b>Ladyman</b>.","Polish: variant of   Lada  .","Hungarian (<b>Ládi</b>): habitational name for someone from Lád in Borsod County or Lad in Somogy County."],"variants":[{"name":"Lada","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Andrzej, Grzegorz, Irena, Lucyna, Witold.","Polish (mainly <b>Łada</b>) and Czech (Moravian): from a short form of the Polish personal name <i>Ładysław</i>, Czech <i>Ladislav</i>, both from <i>Vladislav</i> (Latinized as <i>Ladislaus</i>), a Slavic name composed of the elements <i>vlad</i> ‘to rule’ (from Old Slavic <i>vlasti</i>, later <i>vladati</i>) + <i>slav</i> ‘glory’ or ‘famous’ (from <i>slava</i> ‘glory’). Compare 2 below.","Hungarian: from <i>Lad(a)</i>, a short form of the personal name <i>Ladomér</i>, a Hungarian form of Slavic <i>Vladimir</i> (see   Lado   2, compare 1 above)."]}]},{"name":"Widdrington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative from Widdrington (Northumb), recorded as  <i>Vuderintuna</i>, about 1160."],"variants":[{"name":"Wethington","meanings":["English: habitational name, a shortened form of   Wetherington  ."]},{"name":"Wetherington","meanings":["English (Northumberland and Durham): from Widdrington (Northumberland). The placename derives from an Old English personal name <i>Widuhere</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]},{"name":"Weatherington","meanings":["English (Northamptonshire): variant of   Wetherington  ."]},{"name":"Witherington","meanings":["English: either a variant of   Wetherington  , or perhaps a habitational name from Witherenden in Ticehurst (Sussex), Witherden Farm in Headcorn (Kent), or a lost place called <i>Witherington</i> or similar. The Sussex and Kent placenames probably derive from an Old English personal name <i>Wither</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>denn</i> ‘woodland pasture’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":3,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705193,"age":12,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705195,"age":57,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Widdrington was born in 1325, in England. She had at least 2 daughters with Edmund Widdrington."},"et":{"1325–":"1325–Surnud","1324–Male":"1324–Surnud","1344–Female":"1344–Surnud","1375–1460":"1375–1460","1325–Female":"1325–Surnud","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1324":"1324","Bef 1344":"enne 1344","1344":"1344","1453":"1453","1375":"1375","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","1 May 1375":"1. mai 1375","1328":"1328","Inglaterra":"England","Castle Howard, Yorkshire, England":"Castle